# blue_sky CODEOWNERS — Zelis Engagement Attribution work
#
# ============================================================================
# What this file is — APPROVAL GATE, not review-team enforcement
# ============================================================================
# CODEOWNERS encodes the identity gate: who can satisfy `Require review from
# Code Owners` on a branch-protection rule. It is NOT how the 3-of-3 review-
# team gate (Sage / Iris / Magnus) gets pinned — that's the Repository
# Ruleset's `required_reviewers` clause (see docs/operations/pr-gate-protocol.md
# §6.4 + §7.3).
#
# Two independent gates, both must pass on every PR:
#   1. CODEOWNERS  → 1 approval from a path-owning identity (this file)
#   2. Review team → 3 approvals from Tier B Apps (Sage, Iris, Magnus) via
#                    Rulesets required_reviewers pinning their single-member
#                    teams (reviewer-sage / reviewer-iris / reviewer-magnus)
#
# ============================================================================
# Why CODEOWNERS uses team slugs (not App slugs) on path-specific lines
# ============================================================================
# GitHub's CODEOWNERS syntax accepts users, teams, and email addresses ONLY.
# App slugs (e.g. `bluesky-sage[bot]`) are NOT valid CODEOWNERS entries:
#   https://docs.github.com/articles/about-code-owners
#
# Every agent App is wrapped in a single-member org Team. Naming pattern:
#   Tier A (orchestrators) → @experance-dev/orchestrator-<slug>
#   Tier B (reviewers)     → @experance-dev/reviewer-<slug>
#   Tier C (workers)       → @experance-dev/worker-<slug>
#
# This file references team slugs for path-scoped co-ownership. When the App
# posts a review via installation token, the bot user is recognized as a
# member of the team, which satisfies the CODEOWNERS rule for that path.
#
# ============================================================================
# Codeowner identities — humans first, then teams for substantive co-ownership
# ============================================================================
#   David Wood    — primary approver       → @david-wood
#   Atlas         — codeowner peer, preferred fallback when David is offline
#                                          → @atlas         [TODO: confirm handle]
#
# When David is around, his approval is preferred; Atlas's is the fallback.
# Every Atlas approval is logged in docs/operations/atlas-standin-approvals.log
# with full context — Atlas is a real codeowner, not a workaround.
#
# Path-scoped co-owners pull additional sign-off from the agent whose lane
# the change crosses. Example: schema changes need Helix's worker team plus
# David. The review-team gate still applies on top of all paths.

